Humans as a hub of respiratory viral infections can vastly spread microdroplets and aerosols by sneezing and coughing and in this way even asymptomatic carriers could exhale viruses during the speaking and breathing. [
5 ,
12 ,
13
] The larger virus‐laden microdroplets eventually precipitate, but the water content of smaller virus‐laden microdroplets and aerosols evaporate and create solid residues or droplet nuclei. [
4
] If such residues are small enough (few micrometers to hundreds of nanometers), they could remain suspended for hours. [
